Strings
=======

Basically, vector<char> with a nicer name and some bonus functions.

Nice functions
--------------

* Concatenation via + (someone wrote an operator+ for us)
* += works as well
* s1.find(s2) is kind of like ctrl-f (note return value for no match)
* You also get all the vector functions if you want them
* Length vs size -- seems to be no difference.  String full of `\0` chars will
  still have .size() == .length()
* point out that "asdf" is not of type string, and in particular, you cannot
  add two of them together with +.
* substring extraction via .substr()

Null-terminated buffers
-----------------------

Old school strings...end is determined by a 0 byte.  As noted above, cannot
concatenate easily.

